<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Jacobaea" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Jacobaea othonnae" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="othonnae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Jacobaea othonnae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rare in Greece, known from the floristic regions of North Pindos (NPi) and NE (
<bibRefCitation author="Dimopoulos, P." journalOrPublisher="Botanischer Garten und Botanisches Museum Berlin-Dahlem, Berlin; Hellenic Botanical Society, Athens" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7668013" refString="Dimopoulos, P., Raus, T., Bergmeier, E., Constantinidis, T., Iatrou, G., Kokkini, S., Strid, A., D.Tzanoudakis, , 2013. Vascular plants of Greece: An annotated checklist. Botanischer Garten und Botanisches Museum Berlin-Dahlem, Berlin; Hellenic Botanical Society, Athens" title="Vascular plants of Greece: An annotated checklist" year="2013">Dimopoulos et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). In North Pindos, specifically, there is only one record from Mt. Timfi (
<bibRefCitation author="Authier, P." journalOrPublisher="Phytologia Balcanica, 20 (1): 99 - 137" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7667811" refString="Authier, P., 2014. New floristic records in the Balkans: 24. Phytologia Balcanica, 20 (1): 99-137" title="New floristic records in the Balkans: 24" year="2014">Authier 2014</bibRefCitation>
), while in the NE, there are records from Mt. Athos (
<bibRefCitation author="Boissier, E." journalOrPublisher="H. George, Genevae et Basileae, Lugduni" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7667877" refString="Boissier, E., 1875. Flora Orientalis sive enumeratio plantarum in oriente a Graecia et Aegypto ad Indiae fines hucusque observatarum 3. H. George, Genevae et Basileae, Lugduni" title="Flora Orientalis sive enumeratio plantarum in oriente a Graecia et Aegypto ad Indiae fines hucusque observatarum 3" year="1875">Boissier 1875</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Authier, P." journalOrPublisher="Phytologia Balcanica, 20 (1): 99 - 137" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7667811" refString="Authier, P., 2014. New floristic records in the Balkans: 24. Phytologia Balcanica, 20 (1): 99-137" title="New floristic records in the Balkans: 24" year="2014">Authier 2014</bibRefCitation>
), Mt. Pangeo (a.n. 1983136, LD!) and Mt. Vrondous (
<bibRefCitation author="Authier, P." journalOrPublisher="Phytologia Balcanica, 20 (1): 99 - 137" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7667811" refString="Authier, P., 2014. New floristic records in the Balkans: 24. Phytologia Balcanica, 20 (1): 99-137" title="New floristic records in the Balkans: 24" year="2014">Authier 2014</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Sutory, K." journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="61 - 68" refId="B7669545" refString="Sutory, K., 2021. Taxonomic and nomenclatural notes on Jacobaea othonnae (Asteraceae - Senecioneae - Senecioninae). Phytotaxa 510 (1): 61 - 68" title="Taxonomic and nomenclatural notes on Jacobaea othonnae (Asteraceae - Senecioneae - Senecioninae)" volume="510" year="2021">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sutorý">Sutory</normalizedToken>
(2021)
</bibRefCitation>
, the Mt. Athos plants are somewhat isolated, have woolly-tomentose synflorescences and involucres and belong to the distinct and local subsp. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Jacobaea" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Jacobaea othonnae subsp. anomala" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="othonnae" subSpecies="anomala">Jacobaea othonnae anomala</taxonomicName>
(Sm.) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sutorý">Sutory</normalizedToken>
. The rest of the north-eastern populations are attributed to the typical subsp. 
<taxonomicName authority="othonnae" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Jacobaea" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Jacobaea othonnae subsp. othonnae" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="othonnae" subSpecies="othonnae">Jacobaea othonnae othonnae</taxonomicName>
and have glabrous synflorescences and involucres. The plants of Mt. Achladovouno (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F7677574" captionText="Figure 8. Jacobaea othonnae subsp. anomala from Mt. Achladovouno (photo: P. Doumas)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e81817.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/640534" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">8</figureCitation>
) seem to break this distribution pattern, as they present woolly-tomentose synflorescences, particularly at young age and, therefore, fit subsp. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Jacobaea" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Jacobaea othonnae subsp. anomala" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="othonnae" subSpecies="anomala">Jacobaea othonnae anomala</taxonomicName>
. Our new collection adds a second mountain locality to subsp. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Jacobaea" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Jacobaea othonnae subsp. anomala" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="othonnae" subSpecies="anomala">Jacobaea othonnae anomala</taxonomicName>
and extends its distribution ca. 120 km to the north-east (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7677570" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution map of Centaurea marmorea, Jacobaea othonnae subsp. anomala, Hesperis matronalis subsp. matronalis and Saponaria stranjensis in Greece." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e81817.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/656686" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
